{
  "doc_id": "58431",
  "text": "Ghrelin, a brain-gut peptide, is well known for its effects on hunger [CITATION_1] . Several lines of studies show that females had significantly higher baseline concentrations of unacylated ghrelin than man [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Moreover, treatment with estrogen for 8 h significantly increased the level of ghrelin expression, and ICI-182 780, an estrogen receptor antagonist, completely reversed this effect [CITATION_4] . In our animal study, our findings show fasting also produce antidepressant like effect [CITATION_5] , and fasting also increases ghrelin levels in rodents and humans [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Another study also reported that ghrelin produces antidepressant-like effect in the normal mice [CITATION_10] . Therefore, The present study was aimed to investigate the antidepressant-like effect of ghrelin in the estrogen deficient mice induced by ovariectomy.",
